Data Collection by Luke + Alex Pederson and Steven Jake
Data collection by Luke + Alex Pederson and Rob + Marshall Burgess

Scattered to clear skies- sunny- beautiful- light SE winds- air temp = 52 degrees F- birds singing: Sparrows- Robins- one Blue Jay. Streamside shows stream level about 10" to a foot low.  Water looking the clearest (by far)- of the three sites.  Sample bottles and secchi disk confirm clarity observation.  Water in sample bottle is only a slight yellow- near clear- compared to the other two sites.  Again ... Spencer Kromrie- Gerry Moore- Matt Kromrie- Reiley Hofschulte and Derik Kidd helped with the project.

column1: Note: Even though our perception is a 2 ... for Little Lake Wissota ... it's likely a 1.

column2: Dramatically different in just two weeks ... sediments galore.  Brown water vs very nice clear water ... just a bit yellow on May 5th- 2014.  Air Temp on May 18th @ noon = 63.3 F.
Stillson Creek is looking (relatively)- very clear- again.  Same helpers as Paint Creek on this day.
First time- this year- to see small green particles in water.  Water is still light brown/dark yellow and not green- yet.  Air temp mid-70s.

Until now- Stillson Creek has always been the best looking water- with the deepest secchi disk readings/best visibility of the three sites we're monitoring on Little Lake Wissota.  Now the east side of creek- in the area of monitoring- has scattered- 1.5 foot in diameter- surface patches of algea blooms (first of season) and a noticible increase of the neutrally buoyant green sprigs floating from surface to depth of visibilty.

column1: There's also the first lily pads (this season)- along both shores of the creek in a fairly signifigant amount- with beautiful blooming white flowers.

column2: Von- Ryan- Logan- Robbie and Dave met at the Westside Lafayette Boat Landing @ 9:50 AM to meet Nick and then do our with forcasted water monitoring-  Air tejmperature 74 degrees and humid.  Light overcast.  Very light breeze.

column1: 10:10 AM spoke with Nick and left the dock for Stillson Creek.  Spotted one Red Fox- little bunny and various tweety birds.  Day Lillys blooming.

Green sprigs in water about double from 2 weeks ago.  Algal Blloms more prevelant.  Stratus layer of gren slime appearing on surface.  Worse in areas of stagnat water.  Still swimable in the channel of Little Lake Wisstoa.

column2: Alae sprigs multiplying in all visible levels.  See Wissota Bay report for additional comments for today's (7-26-14)- three monitorings on Little Lake Wissota.

Stillson Creek is (visually)- the worst looking of the season.  Algae sprigs abound at all visible levels of the water- floating blooms have multipled- too. Visually- Wissota Bay has half (of less)- as manny algae springs.  Relativily speaking- the Paint Creek site is still looking pretty good ... as good or better than two weeks ago.  Doe and her two fawns seen along northshore near Paint Creek.  Turtles abound on the logs and there's a sea gull on each "No Wake Buoy."  Sturgeon still jumping-too.

Volunteers: Dave- Pat- Reiley- Hunter and Robbie.  Light breeze- scattered clouds- air temp. low 70s. Sea Gulls and turtles on stumps- sturgeon still jumping.  Stillson Creek continues to suffer the most from algae.  The sprigs and mushy globs are increasing.  That said- most noticeable is the surface of Stillson Creek.  It is now about 45% covered by the "algae blooms."

The two families of Canadian Geese were out and about.  It's now difficult to tell the parents from this year's brood.  Mallards and sea gulls enjoying the water. One silver + gray hawk sped 15' above water- along the creek's shoreline.  Five deer (two doe and three fawns)- spotted along northshore of Little Lake Wissota. Received one report of a Black Bear in the area- too.  However- we did not see it.

column1: Air temperature- low 50s- slight breeze- scattered clouds: Beautiful day!  We've had 10+ inches of rain in the past two weeks.  Many docks have been slightly underwater but not today.   Water level is back to normal.
Volunteers include Pat- Robert- Lachlan- Reiley- Dave and Eric.
